						               													<description>&amp;#228;&amp;#184;&amp;#128;&amp;#231;&amp;#158;&amp;#172;&amp;#227;&amp;#129;&amp;#174;&amp;#229;&amp;#144;&amp;#141;&amp;#231;&amp;#148;&amp;#187;&amp;#227;&amp;#128;&amp;#129;&amp;#227;&amp;#129;&amp;#130;&amp;#227;&amp;#130;&amp;#139;&amp;#227;&amp;#129;&amp;#132;&amp;#227;&amp;#129;&amp;#175;&amp;#231;&amp;#132;&amp;#161;&amp;#230;&amp;#132;&amp;#143;&amp;#232;&amp;#173;&amp;#152;&amp;#227;&amp;#129;&amp;#174;&amp;#231;&amp;#155;&amp;#174;&amp;#232;&amp;#166;&amp;#154;&amp;#227;&amp;#130;&amp;#129; (A momentary masterpiece or an unconscious awakening) is a drawing and deduction game from Japan. Players take on the roles of artists and critics, and create artworks to be assessed by the other players.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;The game has a deck of cards with themes and other with interpretations. A player creates a drawing and displays it in a picture frame. The other players critique the work according to the choices on the cards (ABC, 123) and vote with markers on the rondel. Does the artwork represent A1 or C2 and so on. Then the artist reveals the intent they had written down.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Players then advance their meeples on the rondel depending on how well they did compared to the expectation.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;The game be played with young children by using simple themes and motifs. The intent is to create a happy interaction between artists.&amp;#10;user summary&amp;#10;&amp;#10;</description>
